@summeryael @PeterDellaPenna @FraserMiddleto8 That's exactly it (I think) football marketed itself so well since 92 that's its in a completely different league to other sports. It's got more in common with entertainment industry than any other UK sport. Gap used not to be this big but now it's barely worth comparing.

@PeterDellaPenna @FraserMiddleto8 TV a big reason for that, but so is the Internet, with specialist sites, podcasts etc for your sport of choice, rather than watching whatever is on. It's more stark for cricket which used to be a genuine national sport, but lots of sports face that challenge now.

@PeterDellaPenna @FraserMiddleto8 TV is an issue, but there's a wider trend over 20+ years of sports fandom becoming specialised. You used to get sports fans who watched a bit of everything on Grandstand & ITV. Now people tend to be fans of specific sports only & public generally less aware overall.

In this month's @VoxCricket, I took a look at the history of playing two matches at the same time. Officially, it has only happened twice, a few weeks apart in 1930. But unofficially, it has been a regular occurrence since international cricket began.
In June, @ESPNcricinfo suggested what separate test & T20 XIs would look like for England, India & Australia: https://t.co/JT7LemeTq2
Last week, England's entirely separate men's ODI & Test teams played less than 24 hours apart against Ireland and Pakistan. #ENGvIRE #ENGvPAK
Despite the Women's World Cup being postponed, it is unlikely that it women's teams will double up at any stage, as they have the opposite problem - they play relatively few matches.

It has been suggested that teams could play two matches at the same time, to recover from delays & losses of Covid-19. Back in April, Eoin Morgan cautiously welcomed the idea (https://t.co/HafG5uffVH).
I've got an article in the new edition of @VoxCricket, about the possibility of countries playing international tests & T20s at the same time. A little bit of background:
